00:11:09,466 --> 00:11:11,267
But we did learn something from this.

221
00:11:11,487 --> 00:11:14,409
We have to respect the CPU because

222
00:11:16,354 --> 00:11:19,397
With 8 emitters per character, often multiple characters,

223
00:11:19,437 --> 00:11:21,238
thousands of API calls, you've been there, right?

224
00:11:22,960 --> 00:11:26,643
Often like 50 enemy soldiers, 11 friendlies, 8 vampires.

225
00:11:26,663 --> 00:11:28,324
The vampires actually had 12 emitters each.

226
00:11:29,966 --> 00:11:33,329
All the switches, RTPC values, diffraction values,

227
00:11:33,509 --> 00:11:34,690
it was way too much.

228
00:11:34,730 --> 00:11:36,271
So it wasn't the spatial audio that caused it,

229
00:11:36,291 --> 00:11:37,933
but it was definitely part of the equation,

230
00:11:38,053 --> 00:11:39,074
and we pushed it too hard.

231
00:11:40,675 --> 00:11:42,597
So, we created a...

232
00:11:44,853 --> 00:11:46,274
Well, this brings me onto the next system, really.

233
00:11:46,314 --> 00:11:50,015
We created a culling system for events and emitters.

234
00:11:50,536 --> 00:11:52,977
And this is a kind of a word of warning.

235
00:11:53,297 --> 00:11:54,798
It's not something everyone thinks of,

236
00:11:55,658 --> 00:11:58,200
but it's based on distance to listener.

237
00:11:58,480 --> 00:11:59,980
This is kind of an illustration from in-game.

238
00:12:01,241 --> 00:12:03,322
So outside of their attenuation range,

239
00:12:03,922 --> 00:12:05,703
we could firstly cull the events.

240
00:12:06,324 --> 00:12:08,567
in case the emitters were needed later,

241
00:12:09,208 --> 00:12:11,410
or then we could be even more hardcore than that.

242
00:12:11,450 --> 00:12:12,591
We could just cull the emitters

243
00:12:12,852 --> 00:12:15,455
and stop any updates being called for them.

244
00:12:16,796 --> 00:12:18,939
This was really important during the busy combat scenes

245
00:12:19,760 --> 00:12:20,781
with multiple characters,

246
00:12:21,141 --> 00:12:23,885
and also actually led to a less dense mix in some areas.

247
00:12:23,925 --> 00:12:24,806
We used it to help us there.

248
00:12:26,042 --> 00:12:31,265
And the biggest win and the biggest kind of learning we had from this was make this functionality platform specific

249
00:12:31,785 --> 00:12:36,687
So you can exempt a whole ton of stuff for gen 8 consoles and leave it dense for gen 9

250
00:12:38,308 --> 00:12:39,409
So going back to procedural foley

