311
00:21:47,349 --> 00:21:48,470
Let's move on to the interactive mix.

312
00:21:50,004 --> 00:21:51,524
We have a full runtime mix.

313
00:21:52,305 --> 00:21:53,685
It's the same assets for the characters,

314
00:21:53,705 --> 00:21:56,627
especially for exploration and sequenced sections of the game.

315
00:21:57,867 --> 00:21:59,788
It's a sidechain mix, not HDR,

316
00:21:59,808 --> 00:22:00,909
although we've been looking at HDR.

317
00:22:02,249 --> 00:22:05,131
We do a lot of work with attenuations to help mix focus.

318
00:22:05,491 --> 00:22:06,751
We have a detachable listener

319
00:22:07,152 --> 00:22:08,512
to help the cinematic needs of the game.

320
00:22:09,253 --> 00:22:12,214
And we do something called 50% center bias panning.

321
00:22:14,263 --> 00:22:15,184
Why do we do all this?

322
00:22:15,324 --> 00:22:17,345
Well, we've got a lot of systems running in the game

323
00:22:17,465 --> 00:22:20,888
and we want a clear, focused, immersive, cinematic mix

324
00:22:21,108 --> 00:22:22,169
of all of those systems.

325
00:22:23,970 --> 00:22:26,532
So when we came to dialogue panning, we had a challenge.

326
00:22:27,092 --> 00:22:29,534
The cameras were cinematic third person,

327
00:22:29,554 --> 00:22:30,474
so lots of camera cuts,

328
00:22:31,175 --> 00:22:33,056
often cutting in the middle of a dialogue line.

329
00:22:33,697 --> 00:22:36,639
And our initial approach of full surround panning

330
00:22:38,000 --> 00:22:40,702
led to really harsh jumps in the dialogue there,

331
00:22:40,782 --> 00:22:42,043
both attenuation and panning,

332
00:22:42,063 --> 00:22:43,103
we've switched from side to side.

333
00:22:43,788 --> 00:22:50,332
So we had two options. Option one was the old-school film option of having all dialogue through the center speaker only.

334
00:22:50,512 --> 00:22:54,735
It was safe, but it was lifeless. It just lacked that directionality that game players demand.

335
00:22:55,595 --> 00:23:00,138
Option two of the full kind of 5-1 surround pan had great directionality,

336
00:23:00,338 --> 00:23:03,740
but it led to really harsh cuts which broke the player's immersion.

337
00:23:05,241 --> 00:23:11,285
So what do we do? We rewrote the panning behavior for character audio, actually for all dialogue and foliage.

338
00:23:12,529 --> 00:23:14,450
And we found a sweet spot between the two options,

339
00:23:14,610 --> 00:23:18,132
allowing panning, but only half of what it should have been.

340
00:23:18,833 --> 00:23:22,315
And this was the 50% center bias system.

341
00:23:23,896 --> 00:23:24,637
So how did it work?

342
00:23:24,657 --> 00:23:25,998
Well, with all the character sound

343
00:23:26,038 --> 00:23:27,739
constrained to the front, the LCR,

344
00:23:28,519 --> 00:23:29,920
we would take the character position

345
00:23:29,980 --> 00:23:31,161
relative to the listener as normal,

346
00:23:31,822 --> 00:23:34,984
and play the sound back from a newly calculated position

347
00:23:35,144 --> 00:23:37,265
that had only half the side panning,

348
00:23:37,806 --> 00:23:39,587
thus biasing the center speaker

349
00:23:39,947 --> 00:23:41,828
without constraining exactly to it.

350
00:23:43,292 --> 00:23:46,553
So the example shown here, if a character was off screen right,

351
00:23:47,254 --> 00:23:50,675
rather than their dialogue and Foley panning 100% right as well,

352
00:23:51,595 --> 00:23:53,896
they would only pan 50% right.

353
00:23:55,317 --> 00:23:58,558
Again, if the character was 50% right panned, just on the edge of the screen,

354
00:23:59,338 --> 00:24:02,939
it would be heard from about 25% right panned, center with center,

355
00:24:03,880 --> 00:24:07,201
and as you can see, it's an elastic value, just proportionate to the in-game

356
00:24:07,741 --> 00:24:09,062
position of the emitter.

357
00:24:11,085 --> 00:24:13,748
So it's always playing the majority from the center speaker

358
00:24:13,788 --> 00:24:15,709
when the character emitter is on screen.

359
00:24:16,530 --> 00:24:18,352
And we actually did this for all the character sound,

360
00:24:18,812 --> 00:24:21,214
including anything from sequences, body falls, et cetera,

361
00:24:21,635 --> 00:24:22,816
and of course, dialogue.

362
00:24:23,756 --> 00:24:26,179
So it not only removed the uncomfortable audio jumps

363
00:24:26,239 --> 00:24:28,581
on the camera cuts, but it improved the player engagement

364
00:24:29,381 --> 00:24:30,823
compared to the sensor-only version,

365
00:24:31,043 --> 00:24:33,645
and led to a smoother, more immersive result.

366
00:24:33,705 --> 00:24:34,966
So there's big ticks all around.

367
00:24:36,507 --> 00:24:37,388
Attenuations.

368
00:24:39,087 --> 00:24:43,450
We worldize character sound fairly consistently

369
00:24:43,470 --> 00:24:44,230
throughout all the games.

370
00:24:45,351 --> 00:24:47,993
In this example here with the camera listener distant,

371
00:24:48,873 --> 00:24:51,455
you can see the more nuanced foley is not audible,

372
00:24:51,495 --> 00:24:54,156
the cloth, the acutes, and the gun foley.

373
00:24:55,077 --> 00:24:56,758
Footsteps are audible over long distance

374
00:24:56,838 --> 00:24:59,199
to maintain that character presence and believability,

375
00:24:59,239 --> 00:25:00,320
that kind of connection with the world.

376
00:25:00,880 --> 00:25:03,182
And dialogue, of course, is audible everywhere,

377
00:25:03,342 --> 00:25:06,143
never quiet because it's so important to the narrative.

378
00:25:07,805 --> 00:25:10,807
Moving the listener closer, you can now,

379
00:25:11,548 --> 00:25:14,610
sorry, the more nuanced, subtle Foley is now audible.

380
00:25:15,671 --> 00:25:18,833
And this increases that kind of sense of proximity,

381
00:25:18,853 --> 00:25:20,033
that up close and personal,

382
00:25:20,694 --> 00:25:22,735
which you'd expect from a film mix.

383
00:25:23,916 --> 00:25:26,418
We can also detach the listener, as I mentioned,

384
00:25:27,098 --> 00:25:28,799
and place it anywhere we like in the world.

385
00:25:29,720 --> 00:25:31,481
Now this gives a really cinematic feel,

386
00:25:31,781 --> 00:25:34,503
for example, improving on kind of intimate situations like.

387
00:25:34,991 --> 00:25:37,273
listening to a conversation when you're outside a window,

388
00:25:37,293 --> 00:25:38,534
maybe a cafe or a car.

389
00:25:38,995 --> 00:25:40,296
And we've had these examples come up.

390
00:25:41,397 --> 00:25:43,519
And it also helps us solve occlusion issues

391
00:25:43,579 --> 00:25:44,921
with the new spatial audio system

392
00:25:44,981 --> 00:25:47,023
where cameras are placed outside spatial volumes.

393
00:25:51,127 --> 00:25:53,269
And a quick mention of voyeurism

394
00:25:53,669 --> 00:25:55,090
with our standard attenuation,

395
00:25:55,711 --> 00:25:57,273
which puts the player in a kind of

396
00:25:57,373 --> 00:25:59,435
uncomfortable onlooker situation.

397
00:26:00,284 --> 00:26:05,466
Such as hiding behind a bush, or maybe it's killer cam POV from behind a bush, moving around.

398
00:26:06,066 --> 00:26:12,208
In this situation here, all the distant character sound is audible, but the tree rustle is also audible,

399
00:26:12,308 --> 00:26:15,809
adding to that kind of uncomfortable placement of the viewer or the player.

400
00:26:16,410 --> 00:26:18,570
And this is a great feature for horror.

401
00:26:20,511 --> 00:26:25,313
Moving on to Azimuth. This is a WI's screen grab, of course.

402
00:26:26,517 --> 00:26:30,359
How do we attenuate the sound by angle of emitter from listener?

403
00:26:31,040 --> 00:26:32,701
It's a kind of mise-en-scene approach.

404
00:26:32,801 --> 00:26:35,682
We want to attenuate sounds when they are off screen.

405
00:26:36,823 --> 00:26:40,064
And it's a kind of subtle focus pull for the on-screen sound.

406
00:26:40,925 --> 00:26:44,006
So we decrease the volume, a little bit of high-pass and low-pass,

407
00:26:44,046 --> 00:26:46,288
nothing too clever there, but it's a good result.

408
00:26:47,808 --> 00:26:50,510
So with the character on the edge of the screen,

409
00:26:50,590 --> 00:26:52,491
we have full volume, no filters.

410
00:26:54,233 --> 00:26:57,235
to when the character is behind the listener or the camera.

411
00:26:57,695 --> 00:27:00,157
There's reduced volume and maximum filtering.

412
00:27:00,958 --> 00:27:03,780
So it's a slightly muffled, less focus in the mix,

413
00:27:03,840 --> 00:27:07,723
less clarity, and we have different settings for dialogue.

414
00:27:08,563 --> 00:27:09,664
This is the Foley setup.

415
00:27:09,724 --> 00:27:13,687
Dialogue is, of course, dominant with less attenuated sound.

416
00:27:15,769 --> 00:27:16,870
So with interactive mix,

417
00:27:17,590 --> 00:27:19,091
a quick look at our sidechain bussing.

418
00:27:19,131 --> 00:27:21,973
This is our basic top-down priority.

419
00:27:22,686 --> 00:27:25,128
We use a combination of sidechain volume ducking,

420
00:27:25,268 --> 00:27:27,029
sidechain EQ band ducking,

421
00:27:27,390 --> 00:27:28,971
especially prevalent with dialogue,

422
00:27:29,011 --> 00:27:30,492
taking one K out of other elements.

423
00:27:31,393 --> 00:27:33,634
And we do sidechain compression, of course,

424
00:27:33,654 --> 00:27:34,395
that's super smooth.

425
00:27:35,556 --> 00:27:38,638
And the lower priority sounds can rise up in the gaps.

426
00:27:38,678 --> 00:27:40,860
So this enables us to really focus the mix

427
00:27:40,920 --> 00:27:43,662
on the action we want the player or the viewer to be seeing.

428
00:27:44,563 --> 00:27:46,044
And it keeps clarity, of course,

429
00:27:46,084 --> 00:27:48,526
within the dense cinematic mix that we're aiming for.

430
00:27:50,107 --> 00:27:52,008
And we do some cool stuff, actually, with this.

431
00:27:52,813 --> 00:27:58,897
In Little Hope, the second in Season 1, we added something that placed all the diegetic

432
00:27:58,937 --> 00:28:05,120
sound in fog and through various plugins and RTPCs we had analog control on how those sounds

433
00:28:05,180 --> 00:28:06,021
reacted to the fog.

434
00:28:07,542 --> 00:28:12,705
And additionally for Little Hope, we had control over the pitch of all the atmospheres, 2D

435
00:28:12,765 --> 00:28:12,945
and 3D.

436
00:28:14,587 --> 00:28:16,208
The reason for this, it was matching the kind of

437
00:28:16,248 --> 00:28:19,050
psychological state of the protagonist in that game.

438
00:28:19,911 --> 00:28:23,053
And it was just a really effective way of preceding scares.

439
00:28:23,093 --> 00:28:25,515
We could literally bend reality.

440
00:28:25,695 --> 00:28:26,656
So we have a lot of fun with that.

441
00:28:28,437 --> 00:28:30,199
But the example I want to show today

442
00:28:30,279 --> 00:28:33,921
is a scene called Boat Fight from The Devil in Me,

443
00:28:33,962 --> 00:28:35,242
which was the fourth dark picture.

444
00:28:36,303 --> 00:28:37,204
Came out last November.

445
00:28:38,045 --> 00:28:39,085
It's a high action scene.

446
00:28:39,746 --> 00:28:40,967
And the challenge in this scene

447
00:28:41,007 --> 00:28:42,608
is to keep the intensity of the scene.

448
00:28:42,768 --> 00:28:43,929
And there's a lot going on.

449
00:28:44,822 --> 00:28:46,923
We want to focus on the right action.

450
00:28:48,304 --> 00:28:50,325
So this is our basic mix broken out a bit

451
00:28:50,345 --> 00:28:52,586
to leave some space for other elements.

452
00:28:54,267 --> 00:28:57,289
So unique to the scene is the boat engine revs.

453
00:28:58,890 --> 00:28:59,791
There is a boat in the scene.

454
00:29:00,731 --> 00:29:02,452
So unique to the scene is the boat engine revs

455
00:29:02,692 --> 00:29:04,914
and there's also a boat loop which help fill the gaps

456
00:29:05,374 --> 00:29:07,315
between those key SFX.

457
00:29:09,036 --> 00:29:10,297
We had a lot of water.

458
00:29:12,766 --> 00:29:14,767
Lots of incidental water splashes,

459
00:29:14,807 --> 00:29:16,447
characters falling in the water, etc.

460
00:29:16,968 --> 00:29:18,888
And we had constant water around the hull of the boat

461
00:29:18,908 --> 00:29:19,669
as it was going along.

462
00:29:22,029 --> 00:29:23,550
There was a lot of combat sound effects,

463
00:29:23,570 --> 00:29:26,211
there was a lot of punching and stabbing and kicking

464
00:29:26,271 --> 00:29:27,832
and all that stuff going on on the boat as well.

465
00:29:28,712 --> 00:29:30,653
So we wanted these elements to be very strong,

466
00:29:31,113 --> 00:29:32,674
hold a lot of weight in the mix.

467
00:29:34,254 --> 00:29:36,275
And we of course had a dynamic breath system

468
00:29:36,415 --> 00:29:37,295
for all the characters.

469
00:29:39,202 --> 00:29:42,923
So we had a lot of submixes going on.

470
00:29:43,103 --> 00:29:45,984
We submixed dialogue against the breath system,

471
00:29:46,024 --> 00:29:48,245
basically full ducking on a per character basis

472
00:29:49,085 --> 00:29:49,965
when dialogue played.

473
00:29:51,506 --> 00:29:54,227
There was another submix with the combat sound effects

474
00:29:54,287 --> 00:29:56,588
ducking the main procedural Foley systems.

475
00:29:58,648 --> 00:30:02,590
The water spot effects ducked the more constant

476
00:30:02,710 --> 00:30:06,291
water elements due to, just to allow them to stand out.

477
00:30:08,012 --> 00:30:10,614
And the water spots also ducked the boat engine

478
00:30:11,195 --> 00:30:13,577
due to a frequency range clash in the high end.

479
00:30:15,739 --> 00:30:18,001
Engine revs, of course, ducked the engine loops

480
00:30:18,061 --> 00:30:19,322
to add intensity.

